    version: "2.5.16",
    title_en: "v2.5.16: Per-video SSR pages embed YouTube via youtube-nocookie.com in dev â black-iframe fix on localhost",
    title_fr: "v2.5.16 : Les pages SSR per-vidÃĐo embed YouTube via youtube-nocookie.com en dev â fix iframe noire sur localhost",
    body_en:
      "**Why this change.** On localhost / 127.0.0.1, the per-video SSR page (`/{topic}/v/{date}/{slug}`) was rendering its YouTube iframe with `https://www.youtube.com/embed/{videoId}` directly. That origin issues four `Set-Cookie` headers on every embed request (`__Secure-BUCKET`, `__Secure-YNID`, `YSC`, `__Secure-YEC`), which modern browsers routinely drop on a non-HTTPS `127.0.0.1` origin: Brave blocks third-party cookies by default, Safari ITP filters cross-site cookies on insecure contexts, Chrome's third-party-cookie phase-out blocks them when ÂŦ Block third-party cookies Âŧ is on, Firefox Total Cookie Protection on Strict mode does the same. When the cookie set fails, YouTube refuses to serve the player and the iframe stays a black rectangle â the exact symptom on `/crypto/v/2026-04-26/bitcoin-piege-baissier-explosion-000` and similar URLs.\n\nThe SPA's video cards (`/app/videos`, `/app` briefing) were already swapping to `youtube-nocookie.com` on localhost via a runtime `window.location.hostname` check (added back in v2.0). But that runtime detection doesn't work in SSR â the page is rendered server-side at request time, before any `window` exists.\n\n**The fix.** In `src/app/[topic]/v/[date]/[slug]/page.tsx`, the iframe `src` now resolves the host at compile time via `process.env.NODE_ENV`:\n```\nsrc={`https://www.${process.env.NODE_ENV === \"development\" ? \"youtube-nocookie\" : \"youtube\"}.com/embed/${page.video_id}?rel=0&modestbranding=1&playsinline=1`}\n```\nIn `next dev` (NODE_ENV=development) â `youtube-nocookie.com` (no cookies, no localhost block). In `next build` for Netlify (NODE_ENV=production) â canonical `youtube.com/embed/`. The `playsinline=1` param is added to match `VideoCard.tsx` (consistent mobile inline-playback behavior). The `allow` attribute now includes `fullscreen` (was missing).\n\n**SEO untouched.** The JSON-LD `VideoObject.embedUrl` (line 207 of the same file) still points at `https://www.youtube.com/embed/{videoId}` â Google reads that field for the video rich result regardless of which iframe origin we actually serve to the user. Verified in dev:\n  - HTML iframe: `src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/8udldoRlS64?rel=0&modestbranding=1&playsinline=1\"`.\n  - JSON-LD: `\"embedUrl\":\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/8udldoRlS64\"`.\n\n**`youtube-nocookie.com` â  feature loss.** Same player, same controls, same fullscreen, same captions. The only difference is that no cookies are set on the third-party origin, which is precisely the reason this domain exists (Google ships it for GDPR / privacy-conscious embeds). Many SEO-conscious sites use it by default for both dev and prod; we keep prod on canonical `youtube.com` only because nothing in our setup needs the privacy variant in production.\n\n**Why only dev was broken.** On `https://8news.ai` (production), the parent context is HTTPS with a valid registered domain, so YouTube's `Set-Cookie` headers from `youtube.com/embed/` go through normally â no third-party-cookie blocking heuristics trip. On `127.0.0.1:3000` the parent is HTTP-loopback, which most browsers treat as an insecure context for cross-site cookies â the cookies get dropped, the player refuses to initialize, the iframe stays black. Hence the swap is conditional on dev only.\n\n**Verification on localhost.** Before patch: visiting `/crypto/v/2026-04-26/bitcoin-piege-baissier-explosion-000` â black iframe. After patch + dev server restart: same URL â embed loads, video plays, fullscreen works. The SPA cards (`/app/videos`, `/app`) were already fine and remain so â they keep their runtime hostname check.\n\n**Release.** Bump 2.5.15 â 2.5.16.",
    body_fr:
      "**Pourquoi ce changement.** Sur localhost / 127.0.0.1, la page SSR per-vidÃĐo (`/{topic}/v/{date}/{slug}`) rendait son iframe YouTube directement avec `https://www.youtube.com/embed/{videoId}`. Cette origine ÃĐmet quatre headers `Set-Cookie` Ã  chaque requÃŠte embed (`__Secure-BUCKET`, `__Secure-YNID`, `YSC`, `__Secure-YEC`), que les navigateurs modernes droppent systÃĐmatiquement sur une origine non-HTTPS `127.0.0.1` : Brave bloque les cookies tiers par dÃĐfaut, Safari ITP filtre les cookies cross-site sur les contextes non-sÃĐcurisÃĐs, le phase-out des cookies tiers de Chrome les bloque quand ÂŦ Block third-party cookies Âŧ est activÃĐ, Firefox Total Cookie Protection en mode Strict fait pareil. Quand le set-cookie ÃĐchoue, YouTube refuse de servir le player et l'iframe reste un rectangle noir â c'est exactement le symptÃīme sur `/crypto/v/2026-04-26/bitcoin-piege-baissier-explosion-000` et URLs similaires.\n\nLes cards vidÃĐo du SPA (`/app/videos`, briefing `/app`) swappaient dÃĐjÃ  vers `youtube-nocookie.com` sur localhost via un check runtime `window.location.hostname` (ajoutÃĐ en v2.0). Mais cette dÃĐtection runtime ne marche pas en SSR â la page est rendue cÃītÃĐ serveur Ã  la requÃŠte, avant que `window` n'existe.\n\n**Le fix.** Dans `src/app/[topic]/v/[date]/[slug]/page.tsx`, le `src` de l'iframe rÃĐsout maintenant le host au build time via `process.env.NODE_ENV` :\n```\nsrc={`https://www.${process.env.NODE_ENV === \"development\" ? \"youtube-nocookie\" : \"youtube\"}.com/embed/${page.video_id}?rel=0&modestbranding=1&playsinline=1`}\n```\nEn `next dev` (NODE_ENV=development) â `youtube-nocookie.com` (pas de cookies, pas de blocage localhost). En `next build` pour Netlify (NODE_ENV=production) â `youtube.com/embed/` canonical. Le param `playsinline=1` est ajoutÃĐ pour matcher `VideoCard.tsx` (comportement de lecture inline mobile cohÃĐrent). L'attribut `allow` inclut maintenant `fullscreen` (qui manquait).\n\n**SEO non touchÃĐ.** Le `VideoObject.embedUrl` du JSON-LD (ligne 207 du mÃŠme fichier) pointe toujours vers `https://www.youtube.com/embed/{videoId}` â Google lit ce champ pour le rich result vidÃĐo peu importe quelle origine d'iframe on sert Ã  l'utilisateur. VÃĐrifiÃĐ en dev :\n  - HTML iframe : `src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/8udldoRlS64?rel=0&modestbranding=1&playsinline=1\"`.\n  - JSON-LD : `\"embedUrl\":\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/8udldoRlS64\"`.\n\n**`youtube-nocookie.com` â  perte de feature.** MÃŠme player, mÃŠmes contrÃīles, mÃŠme fullscreen, mÃŠmes captions. La seule diffÃĐrence est qu'aucun cookie n'est set sur l'origine tierce, ce qui est prÃĐcisÃĐment la raison pour laquelle ce domaine existe (Google le ship pour les embeds GDPR / privacy-conscious). Beaucoup de sites SEO-conscients l'utilisent par dÃĐfaut en dev ET en prod ; on garde la prod sur `youtube.com` canonical uniquement parce que rien dans notre setup n'a besoin de la variante privacy en production.\n\n**Pourquoi seulement le dev ÃĐtait cassÃĐ.** Sur `https://8news.ai` (prod), le contexte parent est HTTPS avec un domaine enregistrÃĐ valide, donc les headers `Set-Cookie` de YouTube depuis `youtube.com/embed/` passent normalement â aucune heuristique de blocage cookies-tiers ne se dÃĐclenche. Sur `127.0.0.1:3000` le parent est HTTP-loopback, que la plupart des navigateurs traitent comme un contexte non-sÃĐcurisÃĐ pour les cookies cross-site â les cookies sont droppÃĐs, le player refuse de s'initialiser, l'iframe reste noire. D'oÃđ le swap conditionnel uniquement en dev.\n\n**VÃĐrification sur localhost.** Avant patch : visiter `/crypto/v/2026-04-26/bitcoin-piege-baissier-explosion-000` â iframe noire. AprÃĻs patch + restart du dev server : mÃŠme URL â l'embed charge, la vidÃĐo se lance, le fullscreen marche. Les cards SPA (`/app/videos`, `/app`) ÃĐtaient dÃĐjÃ  OK et le restent â elles gardent leur check runtime hostname.\n\n**Release.** Bump 2.5.15 â 2.5.16.",
